<p><strong>How can you best communicate complex ideas simply?</strong></p>

<blockquote>
  <p>If you canâ€™t explain it simply, you donâ€™t understand it well enough.</p>
</blockquote>

<p>(a) Work really hard toÂ first ensure that I myself understand the complex idea well enoughÂ to be able to discern its most critical components from just the necessary but minor details.</p>

<p>(b)Â Think about what your desired outcome is: Is it to help someone just understand something, or go beyond that and take an action, or something else?</p>

<p>Start with the Simplest Explanation
Think about theÂ KISS principleÂ that has been used for decades orÂ Occamâ€™s razorÂ that has been philosophized for centuries. Simplicity works. Start with something that can be covered, ideally, in a couple of sentences or within a minute or 2. If there is aÂ criticallyÂ important technical detail, mention it quickly. IF the audience wants more detail, they can, and will, ask.</p>

<p>Weâ€™ll start with six basic principles, then move to an applied example.</p>

<ul>
  <li>Give context. Always begin with a roadmap, moving from the satellite view down to the street-level. People need to understand where the details fit in the larger picture.</li>
  <li>Tell a story. Narratives both stick and engage better than facts. They also allow you to ground the abstract in â€œreal-lifeâ€ application.</li>
  <li>
    <p>One analogy is worth five explanations. Our brains shut down easily when learning about unfamiliar concepts. Whenever possible, create a strong bridge between what your audience knows and what youâ€™re hoping to teach them.
Come up with the simplest possible analogyÂ in a domain the audience is familiar with to convey the idea.</p>

    <p>Example: WSJÂ article. The first paragraph summarizes the complex idea and the second one delivers to easy-to-understand analogy.</p>

    <blockquote>
      <p>Software Firms Scramble to Jump Into Containers</p>
    </blockquote>

    <blockquote>
      <p>â€œWhat makes containers so compelling? The technology encloses a program (or a piece of one) in a layer of software that connects seamlessly to the operating system and other computing resources it depends on to run. Putting a program in a container has a number of benefits, but a crucial advantage is that it can be moved quickly and easily from one computer to anotherâ€”say, from a programmerâ€™s laptop to a test system to the cloud. Given the pace of Internet time, harried chief technology officers are desperate for anything that speeds up the process.â€</p>
    </blockquote>

