  <li>Use sound-bites. Your outline should hang on a limited number of â€œhingesâ€. (For presentations and lectures, you should come up with a clear, visual, memorable line to describe each of them.)</li>
  <li>Anticipate â€œdrop-pointsâ€.Â  Are you using terms or concepts that contain potential ambiguity? Are you predicating your argument on an assumption that might not be shared? Are you skipping steps? Donâ€™t.</li>
  <li>Over-narrate the journey. The best advice Iâ€™ve ever received on public speaking was to â€œtell people where theyâ€™re going, tell them where they are, and tell them where theyâ€™ve beenâ€. At each check-point, do a brief recap the help them re-orient.</li>
