  </li>
  <li>
    <p>TheÂ purpose of good SEOÂ is to make sure that search engines promote your website or content when searchers demonstrate aÂ specifically relevantÂ interest.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>TheÂ purpose of good SEOÂ isÂ NOTÂ to make sure your website ranks well for a large dictionary of generic or vaguely-relevant keywords.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Hereâ€™s our roadmap.Â Weâ€™re going to discuss four points this morning: (a) Googleâ€™s perspective; (b) the searcherâ€™s perspective; (c) tactics to avoid; and (d) tactics to use.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Our first topic is Googleâ€™s perspective.Â Understanding this is the key to understanding everything else.Â Iâ€™m going to give you a soundbite that I want you to remember: â€œSearchers are Googleâ€™s customers first.â€Â </p>

    <ul>
      <li>Did you know that Google hires rocket-scientists away from groups like NASA? Youâ€™re probably wondering why. Two reasons. First, they want to deliver the highest quality search results. Second, they want to outsmart con-men.
 Â </li>
      <li>
        <p>Â In the first case, delivering the best results means more folks using Google.This results in more ad revenue for them.Â If I search for a local plumber and end up on a spammy site owned by a shady company, that influences my trust in Google. In the long run, this means decreased ad revenue.Â </p>
      </li>
