    </ul>

    <p><em>5.4</em> So, to recap, Google hires rocket scientists because high-quality search results mean increased revenues for them. Theyâ€™re happy if it means revenues for you, too, but searchers are their customers first. Theyâ€™re willing to protect them vigorously, at great expense.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Â Ok, so now that we understand Googleâ€™s perspective,Â letâ€™s see it from the perspective of the searcher.Â Our soundbite for this point is: â€œIf I ask for a burger, donâ€™t give me a menu; if I ask for a recommendation, donâ€™t lead me wrong.â€</p>

    <p>6a. Letâ€™s use a thought experiment. Say youâ€™re hungry, in a rush, and you know exactly what you want: a bacon cheeseburger. You go to a food court to feed that appetite. When you arrive, you find ten vendors, all of which advertise their â€œdelicious foodâ€. You go to the first one, browse the menu, but donâ€™t see a burger on it. You go to the second, third, fourth one â€“ same thing. You go to the fifth one, and this time the person behind the counter actually acknowledges your presence.</p>

