    <p>Sounds ideal, right?Â </p>

    <p>This is basically all that Google is trying to do: determine the problem youâ€™re trying to solve, then match you with the highest-quality solution for thatÂ specificÂ problem.Â </p>

    <p>6c. So, to recap, searchers are Googleâ€™s customers first, and Google keeps them happy by determining and fulfilling their needs. The customer doesnâ€™t care about them or you â€“ they just want a burger or a recommendation; either a specific thing or a specific direction.</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Alright, now weâ€™re getting to the meat of it:Â the tactics you shouldnâ€™t use. Our soundbite here is: â€œNever offer a cheeseburger to a vegan.â€Â </p>

    <p>7a. As we discussed earlier, some people have tried to â€œtrickâ€ Google into ranking their sites and content higher than deserved. Without getting too technical, how did they do that?</p>

    <p>One of the more popular methods was called â€œkeyword crammingâ€. Think of it like one of those food-court restaurants having a forest of banner-stands in front of their counter, packed with large-text phrases like â€œbest burgerâ€, â€œbest burger foodcourtâ€, â€œbest burger everâ€, â€œfoodcourt burgerâ€, â€œburger, burgerâ€, etc.</p>

